ce:section.ce:para:
On the basis of the novel dual-emission feature of our synthesized DECNDs, both blue emitters and yellow emitters could be utilized to detect Hb under the optimized conditions. For blue emitters (Fig. 3
                        a), with the enhancement of Hb concentrations, the fluorescence intensity increased gradually, and a good linear range of Hb was observed between 0.05 and 300 nM with LOD as low as 20 pM. For yellow emitters (Fig. 3b), the changes of fluorescence intensity showed linear fashion in the presence of Hb with concentrations from 5 to 500 nM, and the corresponding LOD of Hb was 2 nM. Moreover, when excited at 365 nm, the fluorescence spectra exhibited dual emissions at 410 and 530 nm simultaneously (Fig. 3b), thus a ratiometric method for detecting Hb could be constructed by plotting a working curve between the intensity ratios of dual emissions (I530/I410) and Hb concentrations. The fluorescence ratios (I530/I410) decreased linearly with increasing Hb concentrations, and a good linear correlation was obtained in the range from 50 to 500 nM with LOD 20 nM (Fig. S12); this ratiometric detection could be used as a calibration/reference method to estimate the “false positive” of one-emission probe in the application. Hence, both a single emission and ratiometric dual-emission sensors could be developed, and three corresponding linear relationships with different LODs were obtained for the Hb detection; all of these enabled the DECNDs-GO to be a reliable, accurate, feasible, and flexible Hb sensing system against common environmental interferences and measurement errors. Additionally, by comparison of the previous literature for detection Hb (Table 1
                        ), our strategy displayed higher sensitivity and wider linear range based on DECNDs-GO system.
